s":1,"options":["B cells","Dendritic cells","Monocytes","Natural killer cells","T cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised sentinel cells strategically positioned in tissues that contact the external environment (skin, mucosa). They constantly sample their surroundings using pattern recognition receptors and are typically the first immune cells to detect pathogens. Upon encountering microbes, they mature and migrate to lymph nodes where they present antigens to T cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET cells\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EB cells\u003C/strong\u003E are components of adaptive immunity and require activation by antigen-presenting cells before responding to pathogens. \u003Cstrong\u003EMonocytes\u003C/strong\u003E circulate in the blood and differentiate into macrophages in tissues. \u003Cstrong\u003ENatural killer cells\u003C/strong\u003E primarily target virus-infected and tumour cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dendritic cells are specialised sentinel cells that patrol tissues and are typically the first to encounter pathogens","Dendritic cells bridge innate and adaptive immunity by processing and presenting antigens to T cells"],"references":["Tigner A, Ibrahim SA, Murray IV. Histology, White Blood Cell. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563148/","Playfair, J. H. L., \u0026 Chain, B. M. (2012). Immunology at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Nauseef WM, Borregaard N. Neutrophils at work. Nat Immunol. 2014 Jul;15(7):602-11. doi: 10.1038/ni.2921. PMID: 24940954"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67285"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14869"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},